---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '')
---

<Base
  title="Vár docs"
  description="Vár documentation organised by Diátaxis: tutorials, how-to guides, reference, and explanation."
>
  <main class="doc docs-index">
    <nav class="doc-nav" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href={`${base}/`}>Vár</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">›</span>
      <span>docs</span>
    </nav>

    <h1>docs</h1>
    <p class="lede">Organised by <a href="https://diataxis.fr/">Diátaxis</a>.</p>

    <p class="lede">
      Vár is executable documentation for software systems. 
      You can run the documentation, and if the system does something else, you will get an error.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      The documentation typically starts its life as a specification,
      answering the question: *What should the system do*, illustrated by
      *concrete examples*.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      As the programmer/coding agent makes progress towards implementing the
      specification, they get continuous feedback about their progress.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      Sidebar: Try letting the stack traces from failing Vár examples guide you
      in what to do next. This helps you build a more maintainable system.
      Read more *here*.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      When the programmer/coding agent is done, the specification takes on a new life.

      Documentation.

      Remove all the details you don't care about, but keep the examples. Rephrase a little
      and voilá - you have *living documentation* - documentation that never goes out of date
      and tells you when your system's behaviour drifts.
    </p>

    <div class="docs-quadrants">
      <section class="docs-quadrant">
        <p class="kind">Learning</p>
        <h2>tutorials</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href={`${base}/docs/tutorials/hello-var-your-first-spec`}>
              Hello Vár — your first spec
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-quadrant">
        <p class="kind">Tasks</p>
        <h2>how-to guides</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href={`${base}/docs/how-to/wire-var-into-agent-instructions`}>
              Wire Vár into your AI agent's instructions
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href={`${base}/docs/how-to/drive-features-with-var-and-an-agent`}>
              Drive a feature with Vár and an AI agent
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-quadrant">
        <p class="kind">Information</p>
        <h2>reference</h2>
        <p class="empty">Coming soon — spec syntax, step matching, CLI flags.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-quadrant">
        <p class="kind">Understanding</p>
        <h2>explanation</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href={`${base}/docs/explanation/why-var-with-ai-agents`}>
              Why Vár pairs well with AI coding agents
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>

    <footer class="doc-footer">
      <a href={`${base}/`}>← back to home</a>
      <span> · </span>
      <a href="https://github.com/oselvar/var">github.com/oselvar/var</a>
    </footer>
  </main>
</Base>
